doc.title: Coloplast: Positioning into CMD on Sept 2
doc.source_uri: 2025-08-29/JPM Coloplast Positioning into CMD on Sept 2JPM Coloplast Positioning into CMD on Sept 2_2025-08-29

passages.text: Coloplast will host a CMD on Sept 2. Given the operational underperformance of the past couple of years and increasing competition in Chronic Care from Convatec, positioning is bearish with short interest at c. 13 ADTV to cover. Shares have meaningfully de- rated over the past 5 years period with stock trading on forward PE of c. 23x.

Risk/reward looks attractive into the CMD should they set credible targets, which in our view would be in the range of \(7 - 9\%\) organic growth (cons at \(8\%\) ) and EBIT margin c. \(30\%\) by 2030.

CMD focus will be on updated midterm financial targets. Buyside remains sceptical on the current MT targets for \(8 - 10\%\) organic growth and \(30\% +\) EBIT margin beyond FY24/25. Lars Rasmussen, interim CEO, has a balancing act in setting new MT targets, which need to be credible/conservative paving an easy path for the incoming CEO to execute.

In our view, organic growth target of either high single digit or a range of \(7 - 9\%\) (consensus is at \(8\%\) ) could be seen as realistic, underpinned by consensus and could be a clearing event. In the unlikely scenario of an organic growth range including \(6\%\) at the low end, shares could come under pressure as investors could be spooked.

Post the recent CEO succession at Q2 results, the commentary from Lars Rasmussen, interim CEO and Chairman, seems to suggest that they are happy with the \(8 - 10\%\) organic growth range but should they reiterate this range, investors could be disappointed as the upper end of the range is seen as overly ambitious based on the recent track record, business mix and competitive landscape.
On EBIT margin target, a margin closer to \(30\%\) by 2030 would seem more credible than the \(30\% +\) margin target beyond FY24/25.

Investors will also be on the lookout for any potential changes to business structure. For instance a strategic review of Urology could be well received although we see this as less likely given the recent new segment of Acute Care, which includes Urology and WC.

Beyond the CMD, all eyes are on the LCD and proposed CMS pricing. Coloplast are of the view that lowered pricing as well as the LCD would both also come into effect meaning fewer competitors. Overall this could be a tailwind for Coloplast as the proposed CMS price at \(\) 125/\mathrm{cm}^2\$ for all skin substitute products in the outpatient setting for 2026 is higher than the average
